      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Bridge Across the Rio Grande</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof J Huston McCulloch letter objects to view that Mexicans should have only limited access to US labor market (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>George J. Borjas (Op-Ed, July 18) writes that Mexican workers should have only limited access to the United States labor market.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>George J. Borjas (Op-Ed, July 18) writes that Mexican workers should have only limited access to the United States labor market.</p>
        <p>Why is it that a worker who was born in Nogales, Sonora, is a less deserving human being than her cousin who had the good fortune to have been born just across the border in Nogales, Ariz.?</p>
        <p>Our own ancestors were mostly economic refugees whose arrival undoubtedly beat down the wages of the preceding waves of unskilled workers. Why do today's ''huddled masses'' merit any less opportunity?</p>
        <p>J. HUSTON MC CULLOCH  Columbus, Ohio, July 18, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of economics and finance at Ohio State University.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
